Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Instructional Resources Library Technician Toronto , ON Description Permanent, full-time position – Toronto, ON If you have an advanced proficiency in cataloguing, especially the ability to catalogue French language materials and an understanding of copyright fair dealing, and public performance rights, permission, terms and limitations, you’ll welcome this opportunity to join the Toronto District School Board (TDSB)’s Library and Learning Resources team. Reporting to the Unit Coordinator, Professional Library, you will provide operational support for the physical circulation, organization, collection management and customer service support for the Department’s multi-format central instructional resources collection. As an Instructional Resources Library Technician, you will also support the Unit Coordinator in the identification of unit needs and functions, as well as provide guidance and direction to booking and circulation staff. PRIMARY DUTIES More specifically, as an Instructional Resources Library Technician, you will: Provide support in the use of the resource booking system component of the Integrated Library System (ILS); Maintain and monitor online catalogue and resource booking system’s currency and performance;Provide training, and user support and assist in developing documentation;Act as first point of escalation for problems or problem resolution for unit staff and users; Provide direction and guidance to booking and circulation staff; Provide support and guidance to sort, pack, ship, receive, unpack and shelve resources circulating to schools;Troubleshoot, resolve or escalate any issues relating to the timely circulation and return of materials, including lost, damaged and missing items;Support development and implementation of the Library’s space management and collections plan, organize and manage collections, and assess and reorganize shelving arrangements for individual resources;Initiate and process acquisitions of specified resources;Track and prepare statistical reports on collections and usage;Participate in collection analysis and ongoing weeding initiatives through the lenses of decolonization, equity and anti-oppression;Perform original and derived cataloguing of individual items, kits, sets, pedagogical materials, artefact kits, multimedia and other instructional resources in various formats;Respond to requests for known item searching, and refer more complex reference requests to a librarian or instructional team member;Support creation and maintenance of bibliographies and resource guides;Assist the Unit Coordinator in liaising and communicating with vendors and users; andPerform other related duties, as assigned. QUALIFICATIONS To take on the role of Instructional Resources Library Technician, you must have: A two (2)-year Library and Information Technician Diploma with two (2) years’ experience in a related library position, or an equivalent combination of education and experience; Advanced proficiency in cataloguing;Ability to catalogue French language materials in French;Knowledge of children’s and young adult resources that support the K-12 Ontario Curriculum;Understanding of copyright fair dealing, public performance rights, permission, terms and limitations and other basic principles for the use of resources;Ability to provide direction and guidance to staff, and proven team-building skills;Strong communication (oral/written) and interpersonal skills, with a strong customer service focus;Excellent organizational and problem-solving skills, with the ability to prioritize workload;Proficient computer skills, which include integrated library systems, Google Suite, Outlook, Web 2.0 tools, social media, database management, financial applications and media scheduling systems; andThe ability to work independently and within a team. Wage Range: $31.22 – $36.74 per hour This CUPE Local 4400 permanent position, located at 3 Tippett Road, will require occasional travel and the ability to lift and carry packages and containers weighing up to 20 kilograms. Please submit a detailed resume and covering letter as one file in PDF format, and include all relevant documents in your submission, by 4:30 p.m., November 1, 2023, quoting competition #CUPE C-23-0253UE in the subject line, to: Application.Submission@tdsb.on.ca Information regarding Wheelchair accessibility is available online. Only applicants selected for an interview will be contacted. Applications will not be acknowledged in writing. The Toronto District School Board is deeply committed to promoting Truth, Reconciliation and the rights of Indigenous peoples, Human Rights, Equity and Anti-Racism, and the elimination of Oppressive Practices, in our schools, our workplace and in the communities we serve. We strongly encourage applications from all individuals including those with varied lived experiences that can contribute to the diversification of the workforce at TDSB. We strive to meet the accommodation needs of persons with disabilities. Applicants are encouraged to make their needs for accommodation known in advance, during the application process. The TDSB follows a hybrid work structure where some employees may be able to work remotely at times, based on operational requirements. Please refer to Policy P103 &lt; https://www.tdsb.on.ca/About-Us/Detail/docId/2277 &gt;, Flexible Working Arrangements for more information. Compensation $31.22 – $36.74 per hour Closes: 1 November, 2023 Toronto District School Board Toronto , ON Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
