Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? School Library Collection Development Specialist Toronto , ON Description Permanent, full-time position – Toronto, ON If you know how to plan and coordinate on-site collection development services in school libraries and enjoy working both independently and within a team, there's never been a better time to join the Library and Learning Resources team at the Toronto District School Board (TDSB). Reporting to the Cataloguing Librarian, you will assist in the organization and day-to-day operations of the Technical Services team, and plan and coordinate on-site collection development services in school libraries. As a School Library Collection Development Specialist, you will be expected to act as the first point of escalation for problem resolution with bibliographic records and collection development services in school libraries, as well as provide guidance and direction to the Technicians and Assistants, and perform cataloguing of materials according to professional standards. PRIMARY DUTIES More specifically, as a School Library Collection Development Specialist, you will: Plan school library collection development services, which includes gathering technical information about the library collection, arranging for staff resources, and communicating with schools;Liaise with the Program Coordinator, Teacher Librarians and Principals to plan for collection development services in school libraries, weeding and cataloguing library materials in accordance with school plans, the Ontario Curriculum, the principles of equity, anti-racism and anti-oppression, as well as culturally relevant and responsive pedagogies;Lead school library collection weeding services by providing guidance and direction to the team on collection development services on-site at school;Search online databases and download bibliographic cataloguing copy into the Department’s union database;Edit MARC bibliographic records online and edit the Cataloguing Manual;Provide guidance, direction and training, and assist with the coordination of workflow and activities of Technicians and Assistants; Train and support new staff in TDSB cataloguing practices;Act as the planning and processing lead for Library Technical Services at events such as the GTA Resource Fairs, Forest of Reading, etc.;Plan and coordinate customized distributions of resources with TDSB departments and educational partners;Assist the Teacher Librarians with cataloguing, deletions, and other library tasks, as determined by the Cataloguing Librarian of Library Technical Services;Maintain an awareness of new cataloguing trends and developments to improve service and create efficiencies within the Department; andPerform other related duties, as assigned. QUALIFICATIONS To take on the role of School Library Collection Development Specialist, you must have: A two (2)-year Library and Information Technician Diploma with two (2) years’ experience in a related library position, or an equivalent combination of education and experience;Experience in library automated systems and proficiency in derived and original cataloguing;Experience with the Dewey Decimal Classification system;Experience with the MARC format (Machine Readable Cataloguing Format);Experience with weeding school library collections;The ability to catalogue French language materials in French;The ability to provide direction and guidance to staff and proven team-building skills;Strong communication (oral/written) and interpersonal skills, with a strong customer service focus;Strong project management, organizational and time management skills;Proficient computer skills, including library automation and cataloguing systems, internet, and word processing; and The ability to work independently and within a team. Wage Range: $37.44 – $44.23 per hour This CUPE Local 4400 permanent position, located at 3 Tippett Road, requires regular travel to schools and the ability to lift and carry boxes weighing up to 20 kilograms as well as stand for extended periods of time. Please submit a detailed resume and covering letter as one file in PDF format, and include all relevant documents in your submission, by 4:30 p.m., November 1, 2023, quoting competition #CUPE C-23-0255UE in the subject line, to: Application.Submission@tdsb.on.ca Information regarding Wheelchair Accessibility is available online. Only applicants selected for an interview will be contacted. Applications will not be acknowledged in writing. The Toronto District School Board is deeply committed to promoting Truth, Reconciliation and the rights of Indigenous peoples, Human Rights, Equity and Anti-Racism, and the elimination of Oppressive Practices, in our schools, our workplace and in the communities we serve. We strongly encourage applications from all individuals including those with varied lived experiences that can contribute to the diversification of the workforce at TDSB. We strive to meet the accommodation needs of persons with disabilities. Applicants are encouraged to make their needs for accommodation known in advance, during the application process. The TDSB follows a hybrid work structure where some employees may be able to work remotely at times, based on operational requirements. Please refer to Policy P103 &lt; https://www.tdsb.on.ca/About-Us/Detail/docId/2277 &gt;, Flexible Working Arrangements for more information. Compensation $37.44 – $44.23 per hour Closes: 1 November, 2023 Toronto District School Board Toronto , ON Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
