Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Senior High Density Access and Retrieval Associate Toronto , ON Description About Us: The University of Toronto Libraries system is the largest academic library in Canada and is consistently ranked in the top ten among academic research libraries in North America. The system consists of 40 libraries located on three university campuses: St. George, Mississauga, and Scarborough. This array of college libraries, special collections, and specialized libraries and information centres supports the teaching and research requirements of over 300 graduate programs, more than 70 professional programs, and about 700 undergraduate degree programs. In addition to more than 15 million volumes in 341 languages, the library system currently provides access to millions of electronic resources in various forms and over 31,000 linear metres of archival material. More than 150,000 new print volumes are acquired each year. The Libraries' data centre houses more than 500 servers with a storage capacity of 1.5 petabytes. Your Opportunity: Working at the UTL at Downsview location and reporting to the Manager, Downsview, the Senior High Density Access and Retrieval Associate is responsible for coordinating the work of processing materials for, and fulfilling access to, Downsview collections including: contributing to metadata clean up, acting as liaison with other departments, staff and external partners, and acting as a workflow leader. Assists in resolving problems associated with shipments from UTL and external partner libraries and participates in identifying and preparing items for shelving and circulating these items, as needed. The range of duties for this includes: providing information in response to inquiries, processing requests, physical preparation of storage trays, barcoding items, shelving and retrieving with the use of a specialized fork-lift (fork lift training and certification will be provided), opening and closing the facility, shipping and receiving, and assisting with shipping and receiving. May be responsible for other duties such as record maintenance, scanning, and participating in relevant committees and working groups. Performs other related duties, as required. Required Qualifications: Formal Education: Some post-secondary education required; or an equivalent combination of education and experience. Training and certification on the specialized fork-lift used in this environment will be provided. Experience: A minimum of one year of related experience working in a research or academic library setting required. Working knowledge of library systems required. Requires knowledge of bibliographic database searching. Evidence of initiative, analytical ability, and flexibility to respond to workflow demands. Ability to work independently with minimum supervision, and to complete detailed work assignments promptly and accurately. Proven ability to work productively and efficiently in conformity with departmental standards and procedures. Ability to handle large volumes of library materials. Excellent communication and interpersonal skills. Skills: Facility to learn new systems and adapt to new technology and new workflows. Demonstrated commitment to the values of inclusivity, diversity, equity, and accessibility. Demonstrated strong organizational, analytical, and time management skills. Basic knowledge of windows software applications, web browsers, and basic knowledge of word processing and e-mail software required. Experience operating warehouse equipment desired. NOTE: This position is located at UTL at Downsview on Dufferin St. at Steeles Ave. This position is not eligible for a hybrid work arrangement. Closing Date: 10/29/2023,11:59PM ET Employee Group: CUPE 1230 Appointment Type: Budget - Continuing Schedule: Full-Time Pay Scale Group &amp; Hiring Zone: CUPE 1230 (4U) - Step 1: $68,993 - Step 2: $71,694 - Step 3: $74,522 Job Category: Library ServicesAll qualified candidates are encouraged to apply; however, Canadians and permanent residents will be given priority.Diversity StatementThe University of Toronto embraces Diversity and is building a culture of belonging that increases our capacity to effectively address and serve the interests of our global community. We strongly encourage applications from Indigenous Peoples, Black and racialized persons, women, persons with disabilities, and people of diverse sexual and gender identities. We value applicants who have demonstrated a commitment to equity, diversity and inclusion and recognize that diverse perspectives, experiences, and expertise are essential to strengthening our academic mission.As part of your application, you will be asked to complete a brief Diversity Survey. This survey is voluntary. Any information directly related to you is confidential and cannot be accessed by search committees or human resources staff. Results will be aggregated for institutional planning purposes. For more information, please see http://uoft.me/UP.Accessibility StatementThe University strives to be an equitable and inclusive community, and proactively seeks to increase diversity among its community members. Our values regarding equity and diversity are linked with our unwavering commitment to excellence in the pursuit of our academic mission.The University is committed to the principles of the Accessibility for Ontarians with Disabilities Act (AODA). As such, we strive to make our recruitment, assessment and selection processes as accessible as possible and provide accommodations as required for applicants with disabilities.If you require any accommodations at any point during the application and hiring process, please contact uoft.careers@utoronto.ca.Apply to: https://jobs.utoronto.ca/job/Toronto-Senior-High-D... Compensation CUPE 1230 (4U) - Step 1: $68,993 - Step 2: $71,694 - Step 3: $74,522 Closes: 29 October, 2023 University of Toronto Libraries @ Downsview Toronto , ON Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
