Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Data Librarian - Limited Term Appointment Waterloo , ON Description Wilfrid Laurier UniversityLocation: Waterloo, CA Faculty/Academic Area: Library Department: Library Campus: Waterloo Employee Group: WLUFA Requisition ID: 6883 Website: https://careers.wlu.ca/job/Waterloo-Data-Librarian-Limited-Term-Appointment-ON/727970347/ Wilfrid Laurier University Library is seeking a librarian to fill a twelve (12) month, Limited Term Data Librarian position. Reporting to the Associate University Librarian, the Data Librarian will support the collection, management, curation, and provision of access to data across a wide variety of stakeholders and platforms. This position will work collaboratively with faculty, graduate students and librarians to advance Laurier’s research and scholarship goals through support for data management plans (DMPs) and the application of appropriate metadata standards (e.g. DDI). The incumbent will also represent and collaborate with Laurier data partners at the provincial and national levels (Scholars Portal, Digital Research Alliance) to ensure consistency with respect to policy development and system integration. Term of Appointment will be January 1, 2024, to December 31, 2024 inclusive. The Laurier Library has a total staff of 63, including 21 librarians, and provides access to over 70,000 full-text online journals, indexes and e-books and more than 1 million print volumes. As part of the Omni Group of Libraries, Laurier students, faculty and staff may use and borrow materials from 18 member libraries across Ontario, including from local partners, the University of Guelph and the University of Waterloo libraries. The Laurier Library has a strategic partnership with the Brantford Public Library to provide services and materials to users on the Laurier Brantford campus. The Laurier Library serves over 20,000 students in a multi-campus environment at the Waterloo and Brantford campuses, the Faculty of Social Work at the Kitchener location, and at the Milton Academic Centre in Milton. Wilfrid Laurier University is a leading Canadian university known for academic excellence and a culture that inspires lives of leadership and purpose. The University offers undergraduate and graduate programs through the Faculties of Arts, Education, Music, Science and Social Work (Kitchener), the Lazaridis School of Business and Economics, and the affiliated Martin Luther University College on the Waterloo campus and the Faculty of Liberal Arts and Human and Social Sciences at the Brantford campus. Laurier has a distinct commitment to teaching, research, and scholarship, combined with a strong student focus, high levels of student satisfaction and a deep sense of community. Laurier’s innovative educational model purposefully integrates the academic learning experience with an experiential learning component. Responsibilities include: Coordinate the Library’s research data management services, including data curation and archiving, data management planning, advocacy, training, and consultation. Provide support for researchers and students on the collection, storage, preservation, and use of research data Curate research data for Borealis according to best practices and disciplinary norms Consult and collaborate on the development of data management plans (DMPs) with researchers and staff Develop training materials and offer webinars on RDM Engage with Library, Research Office, ICT and other stakeholders to operationalize Laurier’s institutional RDM strategy Advise on RDM best practices, policies, and standards, including Tri-Agency RDM Policy, The FAIR Principles, Principles of OCAP®, and DDI Represent Laurier and participate in national and consortia groups such as Digital Research Alliance of Canada (“Alliance”) Liaise with scholarly communication, repository, and curation colleagues Contribute to socio-economic numeric data and statistics research support and instruction for academic departments in collaboration with subject librarians. Provide in-depth consultation and information services in the discovery and use of socio-economic numeric data and statistics and public opinion polling data, as well as their platforms (e.g., odesi.ca) Support the stewardship and use of the Laurier Ipsos Canadian Public Opinion Polling collection Serve on relevant library and university committees Participate in research and/or professional activity Qualifications: Required: ALA-accredited MLIS, MI or equivalent Knowledge of research data curation (e.g. data organization and description, metadata management and enrichment, developing support documentation Knowledge of best practices, policies, and emerging trends in research data management services, including the Tri-Agency Research Data Management Policy Knowledge of the Dataverse platform Familiarity with data management planning best practices Knowledge of Statistics Canada resources and platforms (e.g. odesi.ca) Familiarity with international socioeconomic data resources (e.g. ICPSR, OECD, World Bank, etc.) Ability to provide effective instruction and training to a variety of audiences (e.g. faculty, students, staff) Demonstrated excellent interpersonal, oral and written communication skills Good organizational and project management skills Demonstrated ability to manage a diverse workload and to work in a changing environment Ability to relate well to diverse groups of faculty, students, and staff Excellent organizational and time management skills. Strong computer literacy and the ability to learn new technologies quickly Demonstrated ability to work both independently and collaboratively as part of a team. Understanding of and commitment to equity and inclusion. Understanding of accessibility best practices and AODA standards. Preferred: Master's degree in a related discipline Work experience in an academic library Experience working with research data and researchers (e.g. research projects, faculty outreach, digital repository work) Experience working with Dataverse Familiarity with quantitative statistical analysis concepts and software (SPSS, R or Stata) Familiarity with DDI, First Nations Principles of OCAP, and Open Access initiatives Professional or scholarly activity To Apply: Applicants should send (1) a curriculum vitae; (2) a cover letter; (3) details (name, position title, organization) and contact information (telephone and email address) for three referees. Please send the application package via email to Anne Linkletter, Senior Administrative Officer, c/o ULAdmin@wlu.ca. Applications must be received by 11:59 pm (EST), Friday, October 27, 2023. Wilfrid Laurier University endeavors to fill positions with qualified candidates who have a combination of education, experience, skills and abilities to successfully perform the duties of the position while demonstrating Laurier's Employee Success Factors. Equity, diversity and creating a culture of inclusion are part of Laurier’s core values and central to the Laurier Strategy. Laurier is committed to increasing the diversity of faculty and staff and welcomes applications from candidates who identify as Indigenous, racialized, having disabilities, and from persons of any minority sexual and gender identities. Indigenous candidates who would like to learn more about equity and inclusive programing at Laurier are welcomed to contact the Office of Indigenous Initiatives. Candidates from other equity deserving groups who would like to learn more about equity and inclusive programing at Laurier are welcomed to contact Equity &amp; Accessibility. We have strived to make our application process accessible, however if you require any assistance applying for a position or would like this job posting in an alternative format, please contact Human Resources. Contact information can be found at careers.wlu.ca/content/How-to-apply/ Should you be interested in learning more about this opportunity, please visit www.wlu.ca/careers for additional information and the online application system. All applications must be submitted online. Please note, a CV and letter of introduction will be required in electronic form. Compensation Min. $68,500 Closes: 27 October, 2023 Wilfrid Laurier University Waterloo , ON Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
